title: zaku_i
body:
A fictional [[mecha]] from the [[Gundam]] series. It first appeared in [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] from 1979.

[b]MS-05B Zaku I[/b]

The predecessor of [[Zeon]]'s massively successful and popular [[Zaku II]] series of [[mobile suit]]s. Commonly referred to as the "Old Zaku", it had a lower output and suffered from overheating issues, but performed well enough against the Federation's weak forces. It was well liked by its pilots, and some units were kept even when the Zaku II was introduced. A number of specialist and customized variants were also put in service, such as the commander type and later on the [[Zaku I Sniper Type]].

title: cesario_(racehorse)
body:
[tn]Named after main character Viola's male alias in William Shakespeare's [i]Twelfth Night[/i]. A likely allusion to her sire's "Supreme Commander" nickname by way of [[Julius Caesar]]: this makes her "Little Caesar".[/tn]
Japanese [[horse|racehorse]]. Sired by [[Special Week (racehorse)|]] and foaled by Kirov Premiere.

Cesario is the first Japanese horse to win in American soil since Haku Chikara in 1959 and the first Japanese winner of an American G1 at the 2005 American Oaks.

Although she was retired the next year, she was particularly successful as a broodmare, with 3 G1 winners: [[Epiphaneia (racehorse)|]] (who became a successful sire in his own right), [[Leontes (racehorse)|]] and [[Saturnalia (racehorse)|]].

title: red_light
body:
This tag is for images with an emmisive red light source. There must be a red light casting a red shade either on screen or offscreen. It's important that the red light is a significant portion of the image

h4. When to use

* You can clearly see where the red light comes from, like a lamp, a bright neon sign, or sunlight coming through something red.
* The red light changes how the picture feels or looks a lot.
* The red light is visible and a key feature of the character (like with Olimar from Pikmin)

h4. When not to use

* If there's only a little bit of red such as with sci-fi suit LEDs that doesn't change the picture much.
* If the surface is red (like they're painted red or a raspberry) and not emmisive
* If there is rainbow light
* More than two different colored light/light sources

h4. Exceptions

* If the picture is heavily desaturated, but there's saturated red lights, you can use this tag regardless of the light size

h4. Example posts
* post #6771544
* post #7115304
* post #6946654
* post #6800023
* post #7139697

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: Color temperature":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_temperature

title: kampfer_(mobile_suit)
body:
A fictional [[military]] [[mecha]] from the [[Gundam]] series. It first appeared in [[Gundam 0080]].

[b]MS-18E Kämpfer[/b]
A high-speed prototype assault [[mobile suit]] created by [[Zeon]]. Intended for close combat, it prioritized speed and armament over any sort of armor protection, being loaded with a variety of weapons - including [[chain_mine|chain mines]], [[bazooka_(gundam)|bazookas]], [[shotgun|shotguns]], [[energy sword|beam sabers]], and [[panzerfaust|panzerfausts]]. 

Piloted by veteran Zeon [[soldier]] [[Mikhail Kaminsky]].

[spoilers]The only known unit was deployed in a colony in [[gundam_0080|the final days of the One Year War]], where it rampaged and destroyed several [[Earth Federation]] [[mecha]] until being destroyed itself by the [[Gundam Alex]].[/spoilers]

For the light novel series, see [[kampfer]].

The [b]Emaan[/b] are an advanced commercial civilization who possess a massive fleet of several transport [[spacecraft]], defensive fighter aircraft and different specialized mecha.  

They are usually called [i]"Techno Gypsies"[/i] by other races and are famous for their selling abilities and trading skills. Emaans fleets and caravans sell advanced technology items in exchange for food and other basic products and resources.

Despite being similar to humans, Emaans [spoilers]have unique features such as a different body biology as well as [[prehensile hair]]. title: kurofune_(racehorse)
body:
Japanese thoroughbred racehorse. Kurofune, which means "black ship" (as in the one [[Matthew Perry]] sailed in to Japan), was named so by his owner, Makoto Kaneko, in the hopes of the horse becoming the first foreign-bred [[tokyo yushun|Derby]] horse. However, his bid to the classic races in 2001 were snubbed by [[Agnes Tachyon (racehorse)|]] and [[Jungle Pocket (racehorse)|]]. The horse would later be on the short list for the Autumn Tenno Sho, only to not make it in to the roster due to [[Meisho Doto (racehorse)|]] and [[Agnes Digital (racehorse)|]] taking up the two foregin-bred slots of that race.

With the Tenno Sho out of the picture, it was decided that Kurofune would be entered in to the Musashino Stakes held the day before that race. At the Musashino Stakes, Kurofune showed immense aptitude for the dirt race and won handily, securing an entry slot for the Japan Cup Dirt in the process. Later on, Kurofune also crushed his opponents at said race; but sadly his racing career was cut short soon after due to tendonitis, and was retired to stud. As a stallion, he has sired the likes of [[Curren Chan (racehorse)|]] and [[Sodashi (racehorse)|]].

title: cowboy_bebop
body:
[i][b]Cowboy Bebop[/b][/i] (カウボーイビバップ) is an influential, critically-acclaimed, and award-winning 1998 Japanese neo-noir [[science fiction]] anime series directed by Watanabe Shinichiro, written by Nobumoto Keiko, and produced by [[Sunrise (company)|]]. 

It is one of the most highly acclaimed anime and is regarded as one of the greatest anime series ever created. It is the highest rated anime series on IMDB top 50 anime of all time, placing at number one. 

Its 26 episodes ("sessions") comprise a complete storyline: set in 2071, the series follows the misadventures and tragedies of a group of bounty hunters, or "cowboys", traveling on their spaceship, the [[Bebop (cowboy bebop)|]].

title: rosary
body:
A type of [[prayer beads]] with a [[cross]] attached to the bottom; the main length of the rosary has five "decades" of ten beads punctuated with larger Gloria beads. Used in the Roman Catholic Church as part of a meditation ritual where the user prays to Jesus Christ and the Virgin Mary. The prayer recites a series of various prayers commonly used in the religion such as the Hail Mary, the Lord's Prayer, and/or the Gloria.

Must have [[beads]] and either a [[cross]] or a [[crucifix]]. If no beads are present, tag with [[cross necklace]]; conversely if no cross is present, tag with the related [[prayer beads]]. Bonus points if it's held in the hand or worn on the belt.

When written with an uppercase, the Rosary refers to the series of prayers. When written with a lowercase, the rosary refers to the beads. For Danbooru's purposes, this tag refers to the bead strand.

title: sonic_the_hedgehog_1
body:
[b]Sonic the Hedgehog[/b] is a platform [[video game]] developed by Sonic Team and published by [[SEGA]] for the [[Sega Mega Drive]]/Sega Genesis [[game console]].  It is the first game in the [[Sonic (series)|Sonic franchise]]. It was released in North America in June 1991 and in PAL regions and Japan the following month. 

The game features [[Sonic the Hedgehog]], who can run at supersonic speeds, setting out on a quest to defeat [[Dr. Eggman]] (Robotnik), a scientist who has imprisoned animals inside hostile [[robot]]s and seeks the powerful [[Chaos Emerald]]s. 

The gameplay involves collecting [[ring (sonic)|]]s as a form of health, and a simple control scheme, with jumping and attacking controlled by a single button.

Development began in 1990 when Sega ordered its developers to create a game featuring a new mascot for the company. After considering a number of suggestions, the developers decided on a blue hedgehog and named themselves "Sonic Team" to match their character. Sonic the Hedgehog, designed for fast gameplay, was influenced by games by [[Mario (series)|Super Mario]] series creator Miyamoto Shigeru. 

Sonic the Hedgehog uses a novel technique that allows Sonic's sprite to roll along curved scenery, which originated in a tech demo created by programmer Naka Yuji. The music was composed by Nakamura Masato, songwriter of the J-pop band [i]Dreams Come True[/i].

Sonic the Hedgehog was well received by critics, who praised its visuals, audio, and gameplay. It is widely considered one of the greatest video games of all time. It was also commercially successful, becoming one of the best-selling video games of all time with approximately 24 million copies sold worldwide across all platforms. Furthermore, it established the Genesis as a key player in the 16-bit era and allowing it to compete with Nintendo's [[Super Nintendo]] Entertainment System console. 

The game has been ported a number of times, and inspired several clones, a successful franchise, and adaptations into [[sonic the hedgehog (film)|other media]]. It was followed by [[Sonic the Hedgehog 2]] in 1992.

title: frida_kahlo
body:
[b]Magdalena Carmen Frida Kahlo y Calderón[/b] (Spanish pronunciation: [ˈfɾiða ˈkalo]; 6 July 1907 – 13 July 1954) was a [[mexico|Mexican]]-[[germany|German]] painter known for her many portraits, self-portraits, and works inspired by the nature and artifacts of Mexico. Inspired by the country's popular culture, she employed a naïve folk art style to explore questions of identity, postcolonialism, gender, class, and race in Mexican society. 

Her paintings often had strong autobiographical elements and mixed realism with [[fantasy]]. In addition to belonging to the post-revolutionary "Mexicayotl movement", which sought to define a Mexican identity, Kahlo has been described as a surrealist or magical realist. She is also known for painting about her experience of chronic pain consequence of a terrible vehicle accident during her youth. She was born to a German father and a mestiza mother.

h4. Some of her works
* [[The Two Fridas]]

A live action film adaptation of [[Ghost in the Shell]], starring [[Scarlett Johannson]] as [[Kusanagi Motoko|Mira Killian/Kusanagi Motoko]] and [[Kitano Takeshi]] as [[Aramaki Daisuke]].

The movie faced some controversy and was accused of whitewashing by people of Asian origin living in the West (Asian Americans mostly) due to it's supposedly largely non-Asian cast, particularly with Johannson being chosen to play Motoko. However, Japanese interviews at the time revealed that many Japanese people did not consider it whitewashing as Mokoto is supposed to be a full body [[cyborg]] thus her external appearance could be of any ethnicity according to them, as well as because of the fact that in the first anime film adaptation of the manga from 1995 the character clearly looks like a caucasian woman.

title: f.o.e.
body:
Special enemies in [[Sekaiju no Meikyuu]] (Etrian Odyssey). A backronym for "Field-on Enemy" in Japanese. Known instead as "Formido Oppugnatura Exsequens" in English, replacing the Engrish with faux Latin.

Unlike regular enemies, they appear in the field and have specific behaviors, like patrolling set patterns or chasing after the player. When first encountered, they are likely to easily wipe out the party; many of the puzzles in the Labyrinth revolve around avoiding encounters with them. If killed, they respawn after 3 in-game days.

In battle, different types of F.O.E have different appearances just like any other enemy, but in the DS era they all appear as a fuzzy orange ball in the field. This led to an association with [[Kedama (touhou)|]] from Touhou.  This also produced the alternate backronym "Fuzzy Orange Enemy".

Made famous by Iosys's F.O.E. song, "えふおーいーとのそうぐう (F.O.E. to no Souguu)".

title: pop_art
body: Pop art is an art movement that emerged in the [[United Kingdom]] and the United States during the mid- to late-1950s.The movement presented a challenge to traditions of fine art by including imagery from popular and mass culture, such as advertising, comic books and mundane mass-produced objects. One of its aims is to use images of popular culture in art, emphasizing the banal or kitschy elements of any culture, most often through the use of irony. It is also associated with the artists' use of mechanical means of reproduction or rendering techniques. In pop art, material is sometimes visually removed from its known context, isolated, or combined with unrelated material.

title: andy_warhol
body: Andy Warhol (August 6, 1928 – February 22, 1987) was an American visual artist, film director, producer, and leading figure in the [[pop art]] movement. His works explore the relationship between artistic expression, advertising, and celebrity culture that flourished by the 1960s, and span a variety of media, including painting, silkscreening, [[photography]], film, and [[sculpture]].

title: james_hunt
body:
[b]James Simon Wallis Hunt[/b] (29 August 1947 – 15 June 1993)was a British racing driver who won the Formula One World Championship in 1976. After retiring from racing in 1979, Hunt became a media commentator and businessman.

Beginning his racing career in touring car racing, Hunt progressed into Formula Three, where he attracted the attention of the Hesketh Racing team and soon came under their wing. Hunt's often reckless and action-packed exploits on track earned him the nickname "Hunt the Shunt" (shunt, as a British motor-racing term, means "crash"). Hunt entered Formula One in 1973, driving a March 731 entered by the Hesketh Racing team. He went on to win for Hesketh, driving their own Hesketh 308 car, in both World Championship and non-championship races, before joining the McLaren team at the end of 1975. In his first year with McLaren, Hunt won the 1976 World Drivers' Championship, and he remained with the team for a further two years, although with less success, before moving to the Wolf team in early 1979. Following a string of races in which he failed to finish, Hunt retired from driving halfway through the 1979 season.

After retiring from motor racing, he became a motor racing commentator for the BBC. He died from a heart attack when he was 45

The 1976 F1 battle between Niki Lauda and James Hunt was dramatised in the 2013 film Rush

title: help:wiki
body:
h4. About Danbooru Wiki

The Danbooru Wiki exists to provide information about topics relevant to the site. 
Primarily, wiki entries are used to explain the usage of the various tags given to posts. 
In addition, the wiki include various information about usage of the site.

h4. Search

The quick search bar will search for titles only. 
For more advanced searching, use the "wiki search page":/wiki_pages.

h4. Wiki pages structure

h5. The body page
The body of the page contains the main reference content. 
Tag pages can include additional tag names above the body of the page. See [[help:translated_tags]].

h5. Left column
* "Wiki Page History":/wiki_page_versions (second name "Recent Changes") contains changelog of a wiki pages. 
* [i]Options[/i] menu for the page:
** Tag History - "posts history":/post_versions for the selected tag on the wiki
** Wiki History - history for the current page
** Discussions - linked a "forum topics":/forum_topics with the current page
** What Links Here - linked another wiki a topics with the current page

h5. Managing wiki pages
* New - create wiki page
* Edit - edit selected page
* History - all changes current page
* Delete/Undelete - aviable on edit mode, mark/unmark this wiki page as deleted.

A fictional [[military]] [[spacecraft]] from the [[MACROSS]] [[science fiction]] series. It first appeared in the [[Choujikuu Yousai Macross]] TV series from 1982.

The [b]Oberth Class Space Destroyer[/b] (オーベルト級 [i]Ōberuto-kyū[/i]) is a human built warship designed as the primary combat starship of the new [[u.n._spacy|United Nations Spacy]] fleet. 

Built with OverTechnology and armed with [[nuclear_weapon|reaction weaponry]], the Oberth compensated for lightweight armor (the only weakness) with a simple, easy-to-build structure, high maneuverability and excellent firepower. A direct hit from one of the Oberth reaction missiles could incapacitate a [[Zentradi]] Standard Battleship of the [[Thurvel-Salan]] Class.

[b]RGM-89DEW EWAC Jegan[/b]

The RGM-89DEW EWAC Jegan is a reconnaissance version of the RGM-89D [[Jegan D Type]]. It has enhanced sensing capabilities thanks to a large sensor unit attached to the head, a second sensor unit on its left forearm, and a large camera unit on its right forearm. The sensor unit on the left forearm has a laser communication device, allowing it to relay gathered information back to the mothership. Since it was never intended to engage in direct combat, the suit's weaponry is kept to a minimum and consisted of a beam saber, a beam rifle and three hand grenades. Its heat emission is extremely low, making it difficult to detect via thermal detection.

title: fez_hat
body:
A short, cylindrical, peakless hat with a tassel on top, commonly found in red. Otherwise known as a tarboosh/tarboush.

Existing in some shape or form around the Mediterranean for centuries, it was popularized by the Ottoman Empire in the early 19th century, with the intent of replacing the turban and act as a unifying piece of clothes (though ultimately gaining various distinct interpretations). Would ultimately be banned in Turkey in 1925 along with the turban under Atatürk to ensure adoption of Western hats, with it only being lifted in 2014. It is worn by various Muslim communities internationally today, as well as Masonic groups.

title: h&k_g36
body:
The [b]G36[/b] is a 5.56×45mm NATO [[assault rifle]], designed in early 1990s and manufactured by [[Heckler & Koch]] in Germany. It was intended to supplant the failed [[H&K G11|G11]] project and the [[H&K G41|G41]] which was too heavy, the G36 features a conventional configuration with short-stroke piston operation. Notable variants include the shorter [[H&K G36K|G36K]], the shortest [[H&K G36C|G36C]], and the [[h&k mg36|MG36]] [[light machine gun]].

The [[weapon]] is characterized by a large carrying handle with an integrated [[optical sight]] and skeletonized [[folding stock]]. It lacks a front sight post as well. The G36 can be fitted with a [[bipod]] or an [[underbarrel grenade launcher]].

title: zastava_m56
body:
The [b]Zastava M56[/b] is a blowback [[submachine gun]] of [[yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] origin, chambered in 7.62×25mm Tokarev [[ammunition|round]], designed for use with the Yugoslav People's Army. Initially a state-funded product, it was later produced by Zastava Arms and introduced in 1961. It saw use in a number of conflicts following the breakup of former Yugoslavia. The M56's external design is based on the captured [[MP40]], both [[weapon]]s featuring an [[folding stock|underfolding stock]], but easily distinguished from the MP40 by its increased length, charging handle on the right side, curved [[magazine (weapon)|magazine]] (32-round is its standard capacity), and [[bayonet]] attachment support. It has similarities with the [[PPS submachine gun]].

Inexpensive and simple to produce and maintain, the M56 also proved to be quite effective at range over its German counterpart due to its 7.62×25mm cartridge having significantly higher velocity than the 9×19mm.
